Amend the European Stability Pact
The European Stability Pact, which supports the euro by setting constraints on the size of budget deficits for Union members, is in danger.
Germany, the heavy weight of the Union, has not succeeded in honoring its budgetary commitments to its European partners.
Moreover, it used its political weight to cover the warning signal of its deficit, which was issued by the European Commission according to the terms of the Stability Pact.
Today, it is France that is playing the bad boy role.
The number two of the Union, not very enthusiastic, has also unofficially declared that it cannot meet its commitment to reduce the budget deficit one year after small Ireland received an official warning about its fiscal policies, despite its budget surpluses, and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signing, the Stability Pact is a real disaster.
In fact, Europe seems deeply affected by the discussions aimed at eliminating it, as well as those aimed at amending it.
And rightly so: the pact is poorly designed and its implementation is flawed.
Limiting the deficit to 3% of GDP is arbitrary and ignores the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
By acknowledging this fact, the architects of the pact made matters worse by adopting two "poorly thought-out" solutions.
They introduced a safeguard clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of a major recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is almost impossible in practice.
Fearing that serious slowdowns could breach the ceiling on deficits, they declared that a normal deficit equated to no deficit at all.
Thus, each year, each country must submit a budget forecast for the next two years demonstrating how budgetary balance will be achieved over time.
Germany's commitment for 2002 was taken in 2001, when its economy was growing at a reasonable pace.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from meeting its goals.
The finance minister, Hans Eichel, reasonably decided not to worsen the situation by adopting a fiscal policy of budgetary contraction.
The Commission, wanting to project itself as the protector of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be made by real politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognized they could face the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was given.
The French situation is different.
During election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, particularly regarding tax relief.
In a country where tax burdens are high, it's not just about political acumen; it's also about economic savvy, especially when budgetary spending is also reduced.
However, France is also a country where everyone benefits from certain privileges funded by the state, and thus, budget cuts are definitively poorly perceived.
Consequently, France cannot meet its targets, and the Commission has expressed its frustration.
But France has become skilled at defying the Union's laws.
Political maneuvering will inevitably follow.
Economists and cynics are not surprised.
The goal of the pact, to establish fiscal discipline among countries sharing the same currency, is entirely reasonable.
However, losing control of their national monetary policy, Union members now have only one macroeconomic tool left: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to go on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to reconcile.
The Stability Pact is too rudimentary and technocratic: the 3% target set by Brussels bureaucrats cannot bind politicians effectively.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we don't have to look far.
The monetary policy faces the same challenge.
It must stabilize prices in the long term while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
In the last ten years, monetary policy has truly been successful.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it is enough to delegate this policy to a competent group, the Central Bank, by giving it the necessary political independence and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any misstep will have to be corrected in the future, it is up to it to exercise common sense.
This has been one of the major improvements in monetary policy in recent years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Of course, some fear losing democracy in the process.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy serves two very different purposes.
The first is structural and redistributive, concerning the importance of the budget and its detailed structure in terms of expenditures and revenues.
Decisions on these matters cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments and be subject to parliamentary approval and management
The second is macroeconomic: it is about defining budgetary balance to manage cyclical fluctuations.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent body.
Thus, Europe's task is clear.
Each country must regain full control of its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term objective is stabilization (or reduction, for some countries) of public debt.
To ensure its effectiveness, the status and mandates of such a Committee must be agreed upon within the Union without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary regulations, without any political decision-making, but rather through common sense.
